// Fused sign × house placement portraits — the core of every placement reading.
// 144 entries: each describes how the SIGN's nature plays out in the HOUSE's
// life domain as one portrait (never a sign paragraph + a house paragraph).
// Voice: second person, behavioral, bold; each entry ends with a trap + move.
// Consumed by getPlacementInterpretation in placementInterp.

const FUSION_FIRE: Record<string, Record<number, string>> = {
  Aries: {
    1: "You don't enter rooms — you arrive, and the room adjusts. Your body moves before your mind has finished the meeting about whether to move: you're the first to stand up, the first to speak, the first out the door. People read you within three seconds because there's nothing withheld to read — the face does what the feeling does. You look impatient because you are, and you'd rather be caught mid-mistake than caught waiting.\n\nYou heal fast, physically and socially, and you rely on that — you throw yourself at life assuming the bruises will handle themselves. Because you lead with your whole body, people follow you before they've decided whether they agree with you. The trap: you mistake starting for finishing and leave a trail of half-fought battles behind you. Pick one door a day and walk all the way through it.",
    2: "Money, to you, is a scoreboard with a receipt attached. You want to earn it yourself, fast, on your own terms — an inheritance or an allowance feels vaguely insulting, because if you didn't fight for it, it doesn't count. You'll launch the side hustle before the business plan exists, buy the thing the same hour you wanted it, and feel physically restless when your income depends on someone else's timeline.\n\nYour self-worth spikes when you close, win, land, sell — and dips hard in the quiet months, because you've fused what I have with what I just conquered. Generous in bursts, impatient with budgets, allergic to slow compounding. The trap: you keep torching stable money to chase exciting money, then starting from zero like it's a personality trait. Automate the boring savings before the next hunt — let the machine be patient so you don't have to be.",
    3: "You say the thing everyone else is drafting in their heads. Conversation, for you, is a contact sport: you interrupt not from disrespect but because your mind finished the sentence forty seconds ago and waiting feels like holding your breath. Texts back in one line. Emails without a greeting. You'd rather be wrong out loud than right silently, and you argue as a form of affection — sparring means you're interested.\n\nWith siblings, neighbors, and the work group chat, you're the one who names the tension everyone was politely ignoring, which makes you either the hero of the meeting or the incident report. The trap: your speed reads as aggression to slower processors, and you lose people who actually agreed with you. Before you fire off the reply, reread it once as the person receiving it — then send.",
    4: "The battles you fight most fiercely are the ones nobody outside your family ever hears about. Home was never a neutral place for you — it's where you learned to defend yourself, and part of you still walks through your own front door braced. You move house decisively, renovate at midnight, rearrange furniture when you're angry, and you'd rather have a loud honest kitchen fight than a week of polite frost.\n\nYou protect your people like it's a job description: cross someone you love and they'll discover exactly how fast you can arrive. But because your instinct at home is action, you fix the leaking tap while ignoring the leaking feeling. The trap: you turn your sanctuary into a sparring ring because calm feels suspiciously like abandonment. Practice sitting through one ordinary, uneventful evening without starting anything — peace is not a threat.",
    5: "You fall in love the way other people jaywalk — suddenly, completely, and against posted advice. The chase lights you up: the first text, the first dare, the first time they push back and you realize they can. You flirt by competing, court by declaring, and you'd rather be rejected by Friday than left wondering until June. Your creative work runs the same circuit — begun in a blaze, abandoned the moment it stops fighting back.\n\nWith children — yours or anyone's — you're the adult who actually plays, full-contact, phone down. Play is where you're most honest. The trap: the second a romance becomes safe, you go looking for a new opening battle, mistaking calm for the death of desire. Learn to pick a fight for the relationship — a shared risk, a trip, a project — instead of against it.",
    6: "You work in sprints and call it a schedule. Give you a crisis, a deadline, an impossible ask, and you're magnificent; give you a Tuesday of maintenance tasks and you invent a crisis just to feel your hands again. You do the whole team's urgent work, resent doing it, and refuse to delegate because explaining takes longer than doing. Your body runs hot: headaches when you're blocked, injuries from treating the warm-up as a formality.\n\nIllness offends you personally — you treat rest as a performance issue and go back too soon. The trap: you burn your health as fuel and your body bills you later, with interest. Build one non-negotiable physical routine — same time, every day, boring on purpose — because your engine doesn't need more fire, it needs a maintenance log.",
    7: "You picked a partner who fights back — or you're bored with the one who doesn't. One-on-one is where your competitiveness lives: you fall for people at full strength, respect through friction, and quietly test whether they'll hold their ground against you. Yes-people make your skin crawl. You propose, commit, and confront faster than anyone around you thinks is wise, and you're usually right about the person and wrong about the timing.\n\nYou'd rather have a real argument tonight than a mediated conversation in three weeks. But the same fire that keeps the bond alive makes every disagreement feel like a title match. The trap: you start conflicts to feel close, then wonder why the person you love flinches when you walk in energized. Once a week, bring them something soft first — the fight will still be available.",
    8: "Crisis is where you become simple. When everything falls apart — the diagnosis, the layoff, the betrayal — you don't freeze, you move, and people who dismissed you as reckless suddenly want you in the room. You take intimacy the same way: fast, direct, all-in, impatient with the slow negotiations most people call getting close. Merging money, bodies, or fates doesn't scare you; waiting does.\n\nYou'd rather rip the bandage, read the will, have the conversation tonight. But depth keeps its own pace, and you keep trying to sprint through territory that only opens to people who stay still in it. The trap: you force the rupture — quit, leave, confess, detonate — just to end the unbearable suspense. When the urge to blow it up arrives, give it seventy-two hours; if it survives the wait, it's real.",
    9: "You don't hold opinions — you enlist in them. When you believe something, it goes straight into your bloodstream: the new philosophy, the new country, the new politics, adopted at full volume, argued at dinner, and lived by Monday. You learn by collision, not curriculum — you book the flight before the guidebook, take the class by challenging the teacher, and change your worldview only when reality beats it fairly in open combat.\n\nYour conviction is genuinely contagious; people reorganize their lives after one conversation with you, and you barely remember saying it. The trap: you crusade for a belief for two years, drop it in an afternoon, and never circle back to the people you converted. Before you preach the next revelation, ask yourself one question about it you can't answer yet — then go find out.",
    10: "Your ambition has a body count of bosses. You're built to be first — first in the door, first with the idea, first to say out loud that the org chart is wrong — and every job either gives you territory to conquer or becomes the thing you conquer. You start departments, ventures, movements; you don't inherit them well. Public failure doesn't haunt you the way waiting does, so your reputation is a highlight reel of bold moves, some glorious, some scorched.\n\nAuthority is your allergy: you respect the leader who earned it and fight the one who was merely appointed. The trap: you win the battle in the meeting and lose the war in the hallway, because victories collect witnesses. Decide which hill actually matters this quarter — then let someone else win a visible one.",
    11: "In every group you've ever joined, you became the engine within a month. You're the friend who texts we're doing this Saturday while everyone else is still saying we should — trips happen because you booked them, the group chat exists because you started it. You compete with your friends and call it love, and honestly, for you, it is: you push people toward futures they were too polite to want out loud.\n\nBut committees make you feral. Consensus feels like watching paint argue, so you either take over or leave. The trap: you sprint ahead of your own community, then feel betrayed that nobody followed at your pace. Once you've launched the thing, hand someone else the keys and stay anyway — belonging is the one race you can't win alone.",
    12: "There is a fight going on inside you that nobody has ever been invited to watch. Outwardly you read as patient, even mild — but you carry an anger with no return address, and it leaks: the sudden sharp comment, the self-sabotage the week before the win, the exhaustion that's really combat fatigue. You fight for everyone else openly and fight yourself in secret, and you file the second one under private business.\n\nYour best courage shows up anonymously — defending the absent, doing brave things nobody ever attributes to you. That's beautiful, and it's also hiding. The trap: unfought battles don't dissolve; they choose their own moment, usually the worst one. Name one thing that made you furious this year, out loud, to one person. The anger is not the enemy — the secrecy is.",
  },
  Leo: {
    1: "Rooms rearrange themselves around you and you pretend not to notice. Your entrance is a production even when you're underdressed — the posture, the pause, the way you make eye contact like you're bestowing it. People remember meeting you; strangers have described you to your face years later. You perform confidence so well that even you can't always tell whether it's switched on.\n\nYour body insists on being expressive: the hair, the laugh that arrives before you do, the wardrobe with a point of view. When you're unwell or unnoticed, you visibly dim, and everyone can see it, which humiliates you further. The trap: you can't let yourself be visibly bad at anything, so you skip every apprenticeship that would make you great. Be a beginner in public once this year — an audience loves a comeback arc more than a flawless run.",
    2: "You buy quality or you don't buy — the generic brand feels like a personal insult. Money is a stage budget: it exists to make life feel abundant for you and, crucially, for everyone at your table, because picking up the check is both your love language and your power move. You undercharge for your actual gifts, overspend on your image, then wonder where it all went. It went to being magnificent.\n\nYour self-worth and your net worth are supposed to be separate accounts; yours share a password. A lean month reads to you as a verdict on who you are. The trap: you go quietly broke financing a production for people who would love you at half the budget. Buy one glorious thing a month, on purpose — and let the rest be boringly, privately rich.",
    3: "You don't tell stories — you premiere them. The same anecdote gets tighter every time: better pacing, a new callback, a pause you've secretly rehearsed. In meetings, at dinners, in the family group chat, you hold court, and people let you because you're genuinely good at it — warm, funny, quotable. You remember exactly who laughed and who checked their phone.\n\nBut listening, for you, is mostly waiting with charisma. You compose your reply during their story, and sharp people notice. Among your siblings you were the narrator — the one whose version became the official family record — and someone quietly resents that to this day. The trap: needing every conversation to end in applause means you never say the unpolished, unfinished thing, which is where intimacy actually lives. Once a day, ask a question you don't have a great follow-up for.",
    4: "Your home is a kingdom with a strict aesthetic and an open-door feast policy. You host like it's a birthright: the good plates come out, the lighting is considered, and guests leave feeling like they visited somewhere. Family is your dynasty — you carry its name, its stories, its reputation like regalia, and privately you believe you're the one holding the whole lineage's dignity upright.\n\nBehind that door, you need what you rarely admit: to be adored by the people who've seen you in your worst robe. When family fails to notice you, it cuts deeper than any public snub. The trap: you perform the matriarch or patriarch so completely that your own household stops checking whether you're actually okay. Tell one family member one unflattering truth about your week — the crown gets heavier when nobody knows you're tired.",
    5: "When you love someone, they know it, the waiter knows it, and possibly the whole restaurant knows it. Romance is your native art form: the grand gesture, the anniversary staged like an opening night, the way you look at someone until they feel like the only lit thing in the room. You love loudly and you create the same way — your projects carry your fingerprints and your face, and false modesty physically hurts.\n\nChildren adore you because you take delight seriously; you play like it's the main event, not the intermission. The trap: you need your beloved to be an audience, and audiences eventually want to be seen too — the romance dies not from conflict but from your solo running long. One night a month, build the date entirely around what lights them up, and take zero credit.",
    6: "You do excellent work and then check who saw. Invisible labor is your kryptonite — you'll gladly stay late on the project with your name on it and quietly die inside doing maintenance nobody attributes. You bring theater to the ordinary: your emails have flair, your desk has a point of view, and colleagues in dull offices orbit you like a space heater. Praise from a boss you respect fuels you for a month; being overlooked once can spoil a quarter.\n\nEven your health becomes a performance issue — you push through illness rather than be seen diminished, and you treat the gym as a stage or skip it entirely. The trap: you abandon genuinely important work the moment it stops being noticed. Keep a private log of what you did well — become your own most demanding, most reliable audience.",
    7: "You married a co-star, or you're auditioning for one. Partnership, for you, is a two-person show with top billing under constant quiet negotiation — you want someone impressive enough to be proud of and devoted enough to keep the spotlight angled your way. Your loyalty runs deeper than most people ever test: once you've chosen someone, defending them is reflex and praising them in public is policy.\n\nBut you keep score in applause. When your partner forgets to admire you — misses the promotion celebration, shrugs at the new haircut — you don't say it hurt; you get grand, cold, and theatrical about something unrelated. The trap: demanding worship instead of asking for warmth, then punishing the shortfall with drama. Say the small true sentence — I wanted you to notice — before it grows a costume.",
    8: "Pride is the last thing you take off, and intimacy keeps asking for it. You'll share your bed, your money, your future — long before you'll share the sight of yourself needing something. In a crisis you become regal: composed at the funeral, generous in the divorce, magnificent at the bedside — and completely alone in the car afterward, because letting someone watch you fall apart feels like abdication.\n\nShared finances turn into quiet theaters of control; you'd rather be the one who covers everything than the one who owes. Being helped embarrasses you at a cellular level. The trap: you perform strength so consistently through catastrophe that the people who love you believe the performance and stop offering. Let one person see you cry this year, on purpose. That's not the throne falling — that's the door opening.",
    9: "Whatever you believe, you believe it in a headline font. Your convictions arrive with narrative — the philosophy isn't just true, it's yours, discovered on that trip, in that book, during the year that changed everything, and you tell it as an origin story. You're a natural teacher because you make ideas feel like events; students, mentees, and dinner guests catch fire off you. Travel is theater too: you don't visit places, you have eras.\n\nYou defend your worldview the way you'd defend your name, because to you they're the same thing. The trap: being wrong about a big idea feels like public dethronement, so you keep starring in beliefs you've privately outgrown. Update one opinion out loud, with full ceremony — watch how much bigger it makes you look, not smaller.",
    10: "Your name is the product, whatever the business card says. You've never wanted a job so much as a stage with a salary — work where the excellence is unmistakably, attributably yours. You rise because people remember you: bosses use your name in rooms you're not in, and you perform best exactly when stakes and visibility peak, which is rare and valuable. Credit, though, is your currency, and you audit it constantly.\n\nA title matters to you more than you tell your friends. Being managed by mediocrity is a special circle of hell you've already done time in. The trap: you choose the shinier role over the more powerful one, mistaking visibility for legacy — applause fades faster than equity. Every few years, take the quiet position that builds something your name is carved into, not just printed on.",
    11: "Your friend group has a sun, and it's you — not because you demand it, but because warmth collects people and you generate it for free. You remember birthdays like a head of state, you toast like it's an art form, and your loyalty comes with pageantry: showing up big is how you love. Friendship with you feels like membership in something.\n\nBut peers are complicated for a person built to be beloved. A friend's dazzling success stirs something you're ashamed of, and you overcorrect instantly with extravagant congratulations. In any group, you'd rather host than merely attend. The trap: surrounding yourself with an audience of admirers and calling it community — then feeling desolately unknown at your own party. Keep two friends who are unimpressed by you and tell them everything. They're the ones actually holding you.",
    12: "The most sincere part of you performs for an audience of zero. Behind the shine you show everyone, there's a private theater — daydreams of recognition so vivid they embarrass you, imagined speeches, the fantasy of being finally, fully seen — and you'd rather be caught undressed than caught rehearsing them. You give anonymously and lavishly, and that secret generosity is the truest thing about you.\n\nBut a hunger you refuse to admit still runs the show from backstage: choices that look humble but are engineered for eventual discovery, self-sabotage timed suspiciously close to your biggest openings. The trap: waiting your whole life to be discovered in a room you never actually enter. Take one creation out of the drawer and show it to five people. Not the world — five. The dark isn't humility; it's hiding.",
  },
  Sagittarius: {
    1: "People hear you before they see you, and see you before you've technically arrived — the laugh travels ahead like an advance team. You walk into rooms as if you've already been there twice and liked it, ask strangers real questions within minutes, and physically cannot do small. Your body wants horizon: you pace on phone calls, treat furniture as a suggestion, and feel measurably worse indoors by day two.\n\nYour first impression is honesty at full volume — people trust you instantly because you're visibly not performing. What they learn later is that you're also not staying. The trap: you announce yourself so vividly that people build plans around a presence you treat as a layover. When you commit to being somewhere, actually land — phone down, shoes off, whole self in the room.",
    2: "Money passes through you like weather. You earn in bursts, spend in gestures, and hold a lifelong quiet faith that more is coming — which, maddeningly for everyone who lectures you, it usually is. You'll drop a fortune on flights and flinch at furniture, fund a friend's dream on a Tuesday, and treat your own bank balance as a rumor you'll check later. Possessions bore you unless they promise experience: the ticket, the course, the gear for the trip.\n\nYour self-worth was never chained to your net worth, which is freeing — and also why the stories outnumber the savings. The trap: optimism as a financial plan, betting the future will always cover the present's tab. Pay your future self first, automatically, before the horizon calls. Freedom is expensive; fund it.",
    3: "Tact is a language you never fully learned, and honestly, you're not enrolled. You say the true thing at the exact volume the room was avoiding it — and the wild part is people forgive you, because there's no venom in it, just aim. You talk in big arcs: every anecdote has a moral, every opinion has a horizon, and precision loses to momentum, so the fish gets bigger with each telling and you half believe the upgrade.\n\nYou learn out loud, think while talking, and treat conversation as travel — the point is to end somewhere neither of you started. Siblings and old friends know you as the one who left, called from somewhere, and made it sound reasonable. The trap: exaggeration spends your credibility in small unnoticed withdrawals. Tell one story this week at actual size — it's still a good story.",
    4: "Home, to you, is a basecamp, not a destination — a place to repack between expeditions. You've lived at more addresses than anyone you know, or you've stayed put and turned the house into a departure lounge: maps on the walls, a bag half-packed in spirit, one eye permanently on the door. Family is a diaspora you genuinely love and reliably leave; you're closest to your relatives from three time zones away.\n\nYou grew up feeling too big for the house you were raised in, and part of you is still proving you got out. But roots were never the cage — you just never stayed long enough to check. The trap: reading every commitment to a place as a trap door closing. Build one ritual that makes wherever you are feel chosen — then defend it like territory.",
    5: "You fall for people who feel like destinations. Romance, for you, starts as adventure or doesn't start: the person with the accent, the plan, the philosophy that rearranges your week — you're in love by the second conversation and booking something by the fourth. You court by expanding someone's world, and dating you genuinely is a broadening experience; your exes are more interesting for having known you, and most would admit it.\n\nYour creativity works the same way — big swings, begun with a manifesto, sustained by novelty. With kids you're the fun one, the question-asker, the one who takes them somewhere real. The trap: the moment love asks for routine, you reclassify the relationship as finished terrain and start scanning departures. Take the person you already found somewhere new — the adventure was never the stranger.",
    6: "A repeated Tuesday makes you feel like you're being slowly buried. You're brilliant at work that's going somewhere — the launch, the expansion, the impossible learning curve — and quietly terrible at maintaining what you built, so you keep hiring, marrying, or befriending detail people to hold the ground behind you. Meaning is your actual salary; give you a pointless task with great pay and you'll be gone, or unbearable, within a season.\n\nYour health follows the same doctrine: extravagant bursts of fitness, then months of philosophy. You overbook chronically because your appetite writes checks your calendar has to bounce. The trap: calling every structure a prison and every routine a small death, until the escaping itself becomes the treadmill. Keep three small daily disciplines and defend them — a horse runs farther on a feeding schedule.",
    7: "You need a partner you can't finish exploring. The vows you actually mean are the unofficial ones: stay interesting, keep growing, never make me lie. You bond hardest with people from elsewhere — other countries, other worldviews, other lives — and the relationship thrives when it's going somewhere: literal trips, shared study, a future with a map on the table. What you fear isn't commitment; it's commitment as taxidermy.\n\nYou tell your partner the truth in doses most marriages never survive, and yours survives because you grant the same radical room you demand. But when you feel fenced, you don't argue — you drift, book things, get vague. The trap: leaving in spirit months before you'd ever say a word. The moment freedom feels short, say so out loud — the cage is usually a conversation you skipped.",
    8: "You handle catastrophe better than closeness. When real disaster hits, you're superb — the one cracking the perfect joke in the hospital hallway, finding the meaning, the silver seam, the reason to keep moving. But sustained intimacy, the kind that asks you to stay inside a difficult feeling without narrating your way out of it, sends you reaching for the exit or the punchline. Depth demands stillness, and stillness is the one country you've never visited.\n\nShared money makes you itch — entangled accounts feel like collateral against your freedom, so you keep an escape fund you've never mentioned. The trap: philosophizing at the exact moment someone needs you to sit in the wound with them, wordless. Next time someone you love breaks open, don't find the lesson. Sit down. Stay. That's the expedition.",
    9: "The question why has been running your life since before you could pronounce it. You collect worldviews the way others collect passport stamps — the semester that rewired you, the religion you left, the philosophy you found at 2 a.m. and reorganized your year around. Study, travel, and belief are one continuous activity for you: you go places to test ideas and read books like itineraries. You're the person friends call when life stops making sense, and your answers are genuinely good.\n\nConviction comes easily; so does the next conviction. You preach with charm, hold court on meaning, and change your gospel every few years with zero embarrassment. The trap: mistaking motion for depth — forty countries, twelve philosophies, one inch deep. Choose one question and give it a decade. Mastery is just travel that stopped running.",
    10: "Your resume reads like a travelogue, and you're weirdly proud of that. You build careers in leaps — the pivot nobody advised, the industry change at your peak, the move abroad that made no sense until it made you. Professionally you're the truth-teller: the one who says in the all-hands what everyone said at lunch, which gets you either promoted or pushed out, rarely anything in between. Ceilings offend you more than failures do.\n\nYou want a reputation for wisdom, not just success — to be known as someone who meant something, taught something, stood for something. The trap: leaping again the moment mastery gets close, because the last mile of any summit is boring and you leave summits to people you privately consider smaller. Stay through one boring stretch. The authority you actually want is only issued at the top.",
    11: "You have friends on four continents and lose touch with all of them warmly. Community, for you, is a wide net, not a knot: the hostel roommate from years ago, the professor, the guy from the airport bar — you collect people through honesty and adventure, and every one of them would host you tomorrow. You're the friend who resurfaces after two silent years and makes it feel like Tuesday, and somehow that's real.\n\nGroups love you for the vision talk — you're the one at the table saying what everyone's life could become, and meaning it. But wide is not the same as held. The trap: ten thousand warm acquaintances and nobody who knows what actually scares you. Pick three people and give them boring, regular, uneventful contact — the kind of friendship that doesn't need a story to justify itself.",
    12: "Underneath all that motion is the thing you're outrunning. Your optimism is real, and it's also a job — the grin, the plans, the next horizon are partly navigation and partly flight from a private question you've never said aloud: what if none of it means anything? Alone, you swing between enormous secret faith and a despair you'd never post, and you medicate the swing with distance — another trip, another course, another reinvention.\n\nYour dreams are epic and geographic; your best insights arrive mid-flight, mid-run, mid-escape. Solitude scares you less than stillness does, and those are not the same thing. The trap: using the horizon as anesthesia, so the wound travels with you, seat upgraded. Stay home one weekend with no plan and let the question catch up. It's smaller than it sounds from far away.",
  },
};

const FUSION_EARTH: Record<string, Record<number, string>> = {
  Taurus: {
    1: "People exhale when you walk in, and they couldn't tell you why. It's the pace — you move like someone who has already decided the day will not rush you, and that unhurried certainty reads as safety. You touch things before you trust them: the fabric of the chair, the weight of the glass, the grip of a new handshake. Your body isn't a vehicle you drive; it's the address where you actually live, and you defend its comforts — sleep, food, warmth — like territory.\n\nThe same steadiness that makes you magnetic makes you nearly impossible to redirect. You will keep a haircut, a wardrobe, a whole version of yourself a decade past its expiration because it still technically works. The trap: you confuse being consistent with being finished. Change one visible thing about yourself this season, on purpose, before life changes it for you.",
    2: "You know exactly what you own, where it is, and what it cost, and you find that knowledge physically calming. Money is not numbers to you — it's insulation, and you can feel a thin bank balance the way other people feel a draft. So you buy fewer, better things and keep them forever: the coat that lasts fifteen years, the pan that outlives relationships. Selling something you own feels like amputation even when you never use it.\n\nBecause your sense of being okay is welded to your net worth, a bad financial month reads to your body as danger, and you respond by gripping harder — hoarding, refusing to invest, saying no to the course or the move that costs now and pays later. The trap: security becomes a bunker. Once a year, spend real money on something that grows you instead of cushions you.",
    3: "You don't say anything until you mean it, which is why people quote you back to yourself years later. In a meeting full of people thinking out loud, you sit like a boulder in a stream, and when you finally speak, the conversation reorganizes around it. You hate being rushed to a conclusion more than you hate being wrong, and anyone who interrupts your sentence gets the same sentence again, slower.\n\nYour opinions set like concrete: the first thing you decided about a topic, a neighbor, a sibling, is usually the thing you still believe. That makes you reliable and it makes you a wall — people around you have stopped bringing you new information because they know it bounces. The trap: mistaking repetition for reasoning. When you hear yourself saying it the third time, stop and argue the other side out loud once.",
    4: "Something is always simmering at your place — a pot, a candle, a playlist that hasn't changed in years — because you build atmosphere the way other people build careers. Home is not where you crash; it's the project of your life, and you'd rather skip the party than come back to an unmade bed. Guests eat well at your table and secretly never want to leave, and you secretly never want them to rearrange anything.\n\nYou hold onto the family version of things, too: the recipes, the grudges, the way holidays are done, all preserved exactly as inherited. Moving house wrecks you for a year; even repainting feels like betrayal. The trap: you keep the rooms comfortable and the relationships frozen. Have the uncomfortable family conversation at your own kitchen table — the house can hold it, and so can you.",
    5: "You flirt with food, with playlists, with the good chair angled toward the sunset — your romance is conducted through the senses, and anyone you're courting will be fed before they are kissed. You are not fast, and you are not casual: by the third date you already know whether this person fits into the long, warm life you're building, and if they don't, no chemistry will change your vote. When you make things — gardens, meals, music, kids' birthday cakes — you make them with your hands and you make them to last.\n\nBut once a pleasure works, you repeat it until it's a rut: same restaurant, same trip, same three moves. Delight calcifies into routine and you call the routine love. The trap: comfort disguised as passion. Once a month, plan one date or project you have literally never tried — novelty is a nutrient you chronically underdose.",
    6: "Same mug, same desk, same order of operations — your workday is a liturgy, and it works. Colleagues set their clocks by you; you're the one still there, still calm, still producing when the sprint-and-crash types have burned off. You don't do busywork theater. You do the actual thing, at your pace, correctly, and you expect to be left alone while you do it.\n\nWhich is why every reorg, new software rollout, and process change lands on you like a personal insult, and why your body keeps the score of your habits so faithfully: the daily pastry becomes the yearly bloodwork conversation, the skipped stretching becomes the bad back. Your routines run you long after they've stopped serving you. The trap: loyalty to a schedule instead of a purpose. Audit one habit each quarter and fire the ones that only exist because they existed yesterday.",
    7: "You choose a partner the way you choose furniture: slowly, by feel, intending to keep them for life. Once you've committed, your loyalty is almost geological — you don't flirt with exits, you don't renegotiate every fight, you simply stay. People married to you know a particular luxury most people never get: the total absence of the fear that you'll leave.\n\nThe cost is that you also stay when you shouldn't. You'll ride a dead relationship for years because leaving means dismantling a life you built board by board, and because some part of you files a partner under things I own rather than someone who could go. Jealousy in you is quiet and heavy, not loud. The trap: endurance masquerading as devotion. Every anniversary, ask the unaskable question — would I choose this again today? — and let the answer actually count.",
    8: "Merging frightens you, so you do it in inches: the joint account comes years after the joint bed, and there's a private savings cushion your partner has never heard about. Depending on someone financially or emotionally feels like handing them the deed to your body, so you keep a quiet escape fund of money, of feelings, of self, even inside a marriage you'd die for.\n\nWhen crisis hits, you are the slow, immovable one — the person who keeps everyone fed through the funeral — but transformation itself you resist like weather. You'd rather endure a familiar hell than gamble on an unfamiliar rebirth, so your losses take twice as long because you grieve while still gripping. The trap: calling stubbornness survival. When something is clearly over — the job, the dynamic, the version of you — set a date and hand it over on schedule.",
    9: "Your philosophy fits in a toolbox: you believe what has held weight, and nothing else. Grand theories bore you; a belief that can't survive contact with a Tuesday is, to you, just decoration. You'd rather learn one subject for ten years than sample ten for one, and when you travel you don't sightsee — you settle in, find the market, learn how locals actually eat, and come home changed in your habits rather than your slogans.\n\nBut you formed your worldview early and you've mostly been defending it since. New ideas get treated like door-to-door salesmen: politely refused before they finish their sentence. Because you already know what's true, you've quietly stopped learning things that don't confirm it. The trap: wisdom hardening into furniture. Once a year, study something that offends your common sense until you can argue its side honestly.",
    10: "Your career is masonry: one brick, then another, no leaps, no reinvention arcs, just a reputation that gets heavier and harder to knock over every year. Bosses learn fast that your yes is real currency — you don't promise what you can't stack — and clients come back because what you build is still standing. You'd rather be trusted than trendy, and you're openly suspicious of colleagues who rebrand themselves every eighteen months.\n\nThe problem is you settle into professional positions like armchairs. You'll stay eight years at a company that stopped valuing you in year three, because the pension is decent and the devil you know pays on the first. Recruiters can't tempt you; inertia holds you. The trap: mistaking a rut for a foundation. When you catch yourself defending a job with the word 'stable' three times in one conversation, update your resume that week.",
    11: "Your friendships have anniversaries. You've kept the same core people since school or your first job, and you tend those bonds like an orchard — slow, seasonal, showing up with food when it matters. You are the friend who remembers, who repays, who still has the concert stub. New people take years to be admitted, and once admitted, they're in for life whether they like it or not.\n\nGroups, though, test you: when the friend circle evolves — new members, new politics, someone moving away — you experience it as a small bereavement and quietly resist. You keep loving who people were five years ago and miss who they're becoming. Your vision of the future is really a better-upholstered version of the past. The trap: curating a museum instead of a community. Invite one genuinely new person into the inner circle this year, and let the circle change shape.",
    12: "There's a version of you nobody gets to see: the one wrapped in the specific blanket, eating the specific comfort food, replaying the comfortable old show for the ninth time. Solitude for you is sensory — you restore yourself through your body, in secret, and you underreport how much of it you need. People think you're endlessly steady; they don't see that the steadiness is manufactured nightly, alone, in soft lighting.\n\nWhat hides in you is appetite. The stubbornness you've disowned, the wanting you think is unseemly — it doesn't disappear, it burrows, and it comes out as midnight spending, secret snacking, dug-in silent grudges nobody knew you were keeping. The trap: comfort as anesthesia — soothing yourself past the feeling instead of through it. When you catch the third consecutive night of numbing, say out loud what you actually want, to one actual person.",
  },
  Virgo: {
    1: "You clock the crooked picture frame before you clock the host. Walking into any room, your eyes do a full diagnostic sweep — exits, tensions, the typo on the welcome sign — and your face does that thing where you're clearly filing corrections you're too polite to say. You present yourself in drafts: the outfit checked twice, the hair fixed in the car mirror, one detail always privately judged insufficient.\n\nPeople read you as put-together and slightly unknowable, because what you're actually broadcasting is quality control. First impressions of you are clean, precise, a little guarded — you shake hands like you're being graded. The trap: you edit your presence so thoroughly that people meet your proofread and never your first draft, then you feel unseen. Once a day, let one unpolished sentence, laugh, or wrinkle leave the house with you.",
    2: "You could recite your bank balance right now, to the dollar, without checking — and probably last month's, too. Spreadsheets soothe you the way baths soothe other people. You research a purchase past the point of reason, buy the sensibly reviewed option, and feel a spike of genuine distress watching someone else spend impulsively, even when it's not your money.\n\nUnderneath the tracking sits a harsher ledger: you pay yourself in usefulness. On days you produce, you feel entitled to exist; on days you rest, some internal accountant marks you overdrawn. So you undercharge for your work, over-deliver on every invoice, and quietly resent both. The trap: pricing yourself by your flaws, which you alone can itemize. Raise your rate — or ask for the raise — one notch past comfortable, and let the market, not your inner auditor, tell you what you're worth.",
    3: "You reread the text three times before sending, and once more after. Your speech runs through an editor other people don't have: you say 'well, technically' more than any human should, you physically flinch at 'could care less,' and your emails have a structure — greeting, context, three numbered points — that people mock and then imitate. When someone tells a story wrong, correcting the date costs you visible effort to suppress.\n\nWith siblings and old friends you're the archivist, the one who remembers what was actually said in 2016. Precision is how you love — you listen closely enough to catch details that make people feel unusually heard. But your mind treats every stray thought as a maintenance ticket, and the queue never empties. The trap: narrating your worry as helpful commentary until people brace when you open your mouth. Before you offer the correction, ask if they want it. Actually ask.",
    4: "Home is where your standards live full-time. The counters are wiped before bed, the labels face out, and there is a system — for towels, for mail, for the freezer — that guests violate constantly and you silently restore. Your family calls you when something breaks: the boiler, the tax form, the marriage. You became the household's help desk so early you don't remember applying for the job.\n\nYou grew up noticing what was wrong at home before you could name it, and you've been quietly fixing your family ever since — booking their appointments, editing their decisions, doing the worrying on everyone's behalf. Care and criticism come braided in you, and the people you love feel both at once. The trap: mistaking maintenance for intimacy, so you're everyone's fixer and nobody's confidant. Tell one family member a problem of yours before solving one of theirs.",
    5: "Even your fun has a to-do list. You research the restaurant, pre-read the reviews, pack the backup charger — and by the time the spontaneity begins, you've scheduled it. When you make things, you make them well and show almost no one: the novel at draft nine, the paintings facing the wall, the song you'll release once it's fixed. In romance, you fall for people quietly and then serve them — remembering the allergy, proofreading their cover letter — because devotion, to you, is logistics.\n\nWith kids and games and dancing, you hover at the edge, refereeing your own performance in real time: was that joke okay, am I doing leisure correctly. Play graded is play cancelled. The trap: revision as a hiding place — nothing you love is ever finished enough to be witnessed. Ship one imperfect thing this month: post it, say it, hit send at draft two.",
    6: "Nobody at work knows how much of the place runs on you, because the disasters you prevent never happen. You're the one who catches the error in the invoice, remembers the renewal date, quietly redoes the sloppy work of others rather than filing a complaint. Your to-do list has a to-do list. Competence flows toward you like water downhill, and your reward for finishing everything is more of everything.\n\nMeanwhile you run your body like a suspect: tracking the sleep, googling the symptom, adjusting the diet — attention that's half care, half surveillance. Every twinge gets an investigation; rest never quite gets approved. The trap: you've made yourself so useful that your value and your workload are now the same number, and burnout will arrive disguised as one more busy Tuesday. Delegate one recurring task this week and do not inspect the result. Not once.",
    7: "You fell for their potential, and you've been project-managing it ever since. In love, you notice everything — the kindness, yes, but also the chewing, the spending, the way they load the dishwasher like a stranger to physics — and your affection leaks out as suggestions. You'd never cheat, rarely rage; instead you audit. Your partner feels simultaneously deeply cared for and perpetually 4 percent below standard.\n\nYou pick people who need finishing, because a partner without problems leaves your love with nothing to do — and then you're exhausted, doing the emotional bookkeeping for two while wondering why you're always the responsible one. You are the responsible one because you hired yourself. The trap: improving someone until they leave to find a person who likes them as-is. Each day, say one specific thing they did right, and let one thing done wrong go unremarked. Forever.",
    8: "When your life detonates, you make a list. Grief, bankruptcy, betrayal — your first response to chaos is administration: notify these people, cancel these cards, research these outcomes. It makes you the person everyone wants beside them in a catastrophe and the person who processes their own catastrophes several months late, once the paperwork's done and the feelings finally get an appointment.\n\nShared money you handle like a forensic accountant — you know what your partner spent before they do — but shared vulnerability is harder. Intimacy is you at your least editable, and being fully seen without time to tidy first feels like being caught mid-mess. So you narrate your depths instead of showing them, analyzing your feelings to avoid having them. The trap: turning transformation into a research project you never actually undergo. Next time you're cracked open, let someone see it before you've cleaned it up.",
    9: "You fact-check sermons. Any belief that wants space in your head has to show its work — sources, mechanisms, receipts — and most applicants fail. You didn't lose your faith so much as flag it for errors, and what you practice instead is a kind of rigorous small-scale meaning: do things properly, be useful, don't lie. When you study, you actually study — notes, systems, the whole syllabus — and travel with you involves an itinerary that has itself been peer-reviewed.\n\nBut squinting at every big idea keeps them all at arm's length, and a life of accurate details can still starve for purpose. You dissect other people's meaning while quietly aching for some of your own. The trap: mistaking debunking for wisdom — you can be right about everything and fed by nothing. Pick one practice you can't fully justify and do it anyway for ninety days, as an experiment. You like experiments.",
    10: "Your reputation is a clean audit. In your field you're the one whose work doesn't need checking, whose numbers reconcile, whose name on a project means somebody competent touched it. You built that name through a thousand unglamorous saves nobody witnessed, and you carry a low hum of contempt for colleagues who present beautifully and deliver garbage — especially when they get promoted past you, which they do, because they talk and you work.\n\nSelf-promotion feels like lying to you, so you wait to be noticed, and waiting is a strategy with a decades-long lead time. You undersell the exact excellence everyone relies on, then feel invisible at review season. The trap: perfect work, silent worker, someone else's applause. Keep a running file of what you've fixed, shipped, and saved — and read three items from it, out loud, in every performance review and interview.",
    11: "You're the friend who remembers the allergy, texts on the anniversary of the bad thing, and shows up to help move with your own tape gun. In any group you drift toward the operational center: making the reservation, collecting the money, fixing the plan everyone else vibed into existence. Your people count on you the way they count on gravity — constantly, and without ever thinking about it.\n\nThat's the bruise. You keep score quietly — every favor logged, every unreciprocated pickup from the airport — and you'd rather compost your resentment than risk asking for help and being a burden. So you serve the community, critique it under your breath, and wonder why belonging feels like staffing. The trap: being essential to everyone and close to no one. Next time you're struggling, ask a friend for something specific and inconvenient, and let them do it imperfectly.",
    12: "The commentary never stops. Behind your composed exterior runs a private radio station reviewing everything you did today — the dumb joke at 11:40, the email tone, the thing you said in 2019 — hosted by a critic who works nights, weekends, and holidays. Nobody knows how hard you are on yourself, because the flogging happens in a soundproofed room, and by morning you're back to being pleasantly capable.\n\nEven your escapes are productive: you rest by reorganizing, unwind by researching, relax by fixing something small. Pure stillness feels like a mistake being made. But the errors you refuse to forgive don't file away — they compost into fatigue, insomnia, that low ambient guilt with no invoice attached. The trap: perfecting yourself in private until the maintenance becomes the prison. Once a week, do one useless thing — badly, on purpose — and tell the night-shift critic it was intentional.",
  },
  Capricorn: {
    1: "You were forty at fourteen. People meet you and instinctively sit up straighter — something in your bearing reads as authority before you've said a word, and strangers keep assuming you're in charge until, eventually, you are. You enter rooms like you have an agenda even at parties, dress like a person who reads contracts, and smile on a slight delay, as if warmth has to clear security first.\n\nThat gravity opens doors, and it also builds a wall: people respect you instantly and take years to feel they know you, because your default setting is composed, and composed is a kind of hiding. You age in reverse — lighter at fifty than fifteen — but only if you let the guard down on purpose. The trap: armor so good you're lonely inside it. Let someone see you flustered this month, and watch them relax around you for the first time.",
    2: "Money, to you, is a ladder with a summit you've already surveyed. You knew your number early — the figure that means safe, the age that means done — and you've been climbing toward it with a discipline that unnerves people: automatic transfers, denied impulses, the same modest car while your accounts quietly compound. You'd rather own one excellent thing than ten adequate ones, and you regard debt the way other people regard cliff edges.\n\nBut somewhere the ladder became the view. You defer the trip, the table upgrade, the generous gesture — not because you can't afford them, but because spending on joy feels like leaking. And your self-respect is indexed to your net worth so tightly that a lean year reads as a character verdict. The trap: dying rich and living broke. Spend a planned, guilt-free percentage on delight every single month, like a bill.",
    3: "You speak in conclusions. While others think out loud, you run the argument privately, stress-test it, and release only the finished verdict — which is why your emails are four sentences, your meetings end early, and people twice your age quote you in rooms you're not in. Small talk physically drains you; you'd rather exchange one useful sentence than an hour of pleasant noise, and you answer questions people were still in the middle of asking.\n\nAmong siblings and old friends, you're the one they call for the serious things — the diagnosis, the contract, the plan — and rarely for the silly ones, because somewhere along the way your words all became load-bearing. What you never learned to say is the unstrategic thing: the fear, the affection, the doubt still in draft form. The trap: sounding certain even when you're breaking. Tell someone a problem you haven't solved yet — before you've solved it.",
    4: "At some point — earlier than anyone should — you became the parent of your own family. You're the one who handles the estate paperwork, referees the sibling disputes, pays for the roof nobody else noticed leaking. Home, as you build it, is a fortress with a mortgage schedule: you didn't just want a house, you wanted an unassailable position, and duty is the language your love speaks most fluently.\n\nSomewhere in your childhood there was a shortage — of money, of warmth, of a functioning adult — and you've spent your life making sure it never recurs, running your household like an institution that must not fail. But institutions don't hug back, and your family gets your provision more often than your presence. The trap: providing so relentlessly that you're the most reliable and least known person at your own dinner table. Sit down tonight with nothing to fix, and stay.",
    5: "You schedule joy, and then you're proud of the schedule. Hobbies become disciplines within a month — the casual run acquires a training plan, the doodling becomes a portfolio, the poker night develops standings. You keep score during activities that don't have scores. In romance you court like you're building something: deliberate, exclusive, faintly formal, with a horizon in mind by the second date, because playing without stakes strikes you as a waste of a heart.\n\nChildren and games unmask you — you're either magnificent with kids, meeting their seriousness with respect, or you're checking your phone through the fun you booked. Somewhere a younger you learned that performance earned love, and now you can't create anything without auditioning. The trap: turning every pleasure into a job and every date into a merger. Do one delightful thing this week that produces nothing — no progress, no content, no score.",
    6: "You work sick. You've filed reports with a fever, taken calls from hospital corridors, and privately regard your body as a junior employee whose complaints are noted and overruled. Your daily systems are governmental in their rigor — the alarm never negotiated with, the inbox at zero, the routine executed regardless of mood, because mood, in your view, is not a scheduling factor.\n\nColleagues call you a machine and mean it as praise; your body will eventually disagree, in writing. You treat rest as a reward for finished work in a life where the work is never finished, so the reward never quite arrives — and the stiff back, the grinding jaw, the 2 a.m. wake-ups are the invoice printing slowly. The trap: earning your way out of self-care indefinitely. Put rest on the actual calendar with the actual meetings, and defend it like a deliverable.",
    7: "You vet lovers like hires. Somewhere behind your eyes is a quiet interview running — do they handle money, keep promises, hold up under pressure — and passion alone has never once gotten a candidate past it. You marry (or bond) for the long arc: you show love by handling things, keeping every promise, standing granite-still in the crises that scatter other couples. Your word, once given, is infrastructure.\n\nBut you run the relationship like an operation — dividing labor, tracking obligations, being impeccable — and impeccable is hard to cuddle. Your partner gets your reliability daily and your vulnerability annually, and being needed emotionally flusters you more than any deadline ever has. The trap: becoming your spouse's most trusted colleague while somebody easier gets the warmth. Once a week, bring your partner a need instead of a solution, and let them be strong for you.",
    8: "You do grief efficiently, which alarms people. When the diagnosis lands or the money vanishes, you go cold, capable, almost calm — executing the crisis while others drown in it — and then, months later, alone in a parked car, you finally let one wave through, on your terms, with the door locked. Losing control in front of a witness ranks among your private definitions of hell.\n\nShared finances you'll manage brilliantly and dominate quietly: you'll carry a partner's debt without complaint but struggle to let them carry an ounce of yours, because owing is exposure and exposure is the one debt you refuse. Depths get entered the way you enter everything — alone, prepared, jaw set. The trap: surviving everything solo and calling that intimacy. Next crisis, let one person watch you not cope for ten minutes. That's the whole assignment.",
    9: "You distrust any wisdom that arrived without a receipt. Beliefs, in your book, are earned — tested against decades, paid for in consequences — so you keep a short, unglamorous creed: work works, character compounds, most shortcuts are loans. You read history instead of horoscopes and biographies instead of manifestos, mining the dead for strategy. When you travel, you're studying — how this city runs, what this culture builds — and you come home with frameworks, not souvenirs.\n\nThe austerity is the blind spot. You dismiss whatever can't prove itself in results — wonder, mysticism, plain unprofitable awe — and a worldview built only from evidence eventually becomes a ledger where a life should be. Meaning isn't always efficient. The trap: being too realistic to hope, and calling that maturity. Once this year, chase a question with no career value whatsoever, and follow it further than is sensible.",
    10: "The summit has had your name on it since childhood. While classmates dreamed, you drafted: you knew the field, the title, the trajectory, and you've been executing through every setback with a patience that reads as inevitability. You take the stairs while others chase elevators, and decades in, people call you an overnight success with a straight face. Your reputation is your true net worth and you know its price to the penny.\n\nBut the mountain lies. Every summit reveals another, and you've postponed being satisfied so many times that arrival has become a foreign country you can describe but never enter. Meanwhile the title is fusing to your spine — lose the job and you'd need a season to remember who's left. The trap: becoming your resume. Write down what 'enough' actually is, in numbers, and when you hit it, celebrate like you mean it.",
    11: "You audit your circle. Friends, in your world, are chosen like board members — for character, competence, and staying power — and your inner ring is small, old, and vetted by years. You're the one the group quietly defers to: the planner of the reunion, the executor of the estate, the person called when a friend's life needs an adult. You network upward without shame and consider it honesty; time is capital and you invest it.\n\nThe strategy shows, though. People sense the vetting, and warmth withheld until usefulness is proven means you're respected in every room and missed in few. You keep friendships in maintenance mode — holiday messages, milestone attendance — while the daily, pointless contact that actually makes people close gets deprioritized as overhead. The trap: a network where a family of friends should be. Call one friend this week for no reason, about nothing, and stay on past the update.",
    12: "No one has ever seen you exhausted — that's by design. You process fear, doubt, and depletion in a private back office, off the books, and emerge each morning balanced and presentable. What you hide isn't scandal; it's fatigue, and the terror underneath the entire operation: that if you ever stopped producing, the people around you would have no further use for you. So you never stop, and the hypothesis goes untested.\n\nAlone is where you actually breathe — you crave solitude like oxygen and then use it to do more work, because unstructured stillness lets the dread in. Your dreams keep sending memos about collapse; you file them unread. The trap: your discipline is also your sedative, and it's numbing you on schedule. Take one full day with no output, no errands, no optimizing — and notice that everyone still loves you at sundown.",
  },
};

const FUSION_AIR: Record<string, Record<number, string>> = {
  Gemini: {
    1: "You enter a room the way a breeze does — already halfway across it before anyone registers the door opened. You talk with your hands, clock every face in seconds, and within minutes you have found the three most interesting people there and started something with each of them. People consistently guess you younger than you are, because your face moves like weather: nothing sits on it long enough to leave a line.\n\nBut quickness is also your armor. When a conversation threatens to get heavy, you get funny; when someone looks at you too long, you change the subject to them. The trap: people fall for the sparkle and never get offered the substance, then you resent them for knowing you shallowly. Next time someone asks how you actually are, stand still and answer the question.",
    2: "Money arrives through your mouth and your wits — the pitch, the side hustle, the clever flip, the skill you picked up last month and are already selling. One income stream bores you, so you run three, and you can talk your way into a paycheck faster than most people can format a resume. You spend the way you earn: on impulse, on novelty, on the course you will half-finish and the gadget that promised to change everything.\n\nUnderneath it, your self-worth is wired to being interesting — you would rather be broke and fascinating than rich and dull, and your bank account knows it. The trap: financial chaos disguised as flexibility, ten open loops and nothing compounding anywhere. Pick one boring vehicle — automatic transfer, index fund, anything — and let it run untouched while you play with the rest.",
    3: "Your mind runs a group chat with itself, and you are all twelve participants. You think by talking, read four things at once, and finish other people's sentences — accurately, which is the annoying part. Texts from you arrive in bursts of five. Siblings, neighbors, the barista: everyone in your daily orbit gets the commentary track, and half your best ideas were discovered mid-sentence, out loud, to someone who only asked about your day.\n\nThe speed is real intelligence, not performance. But the trap is built in: you talk past your own depth, answering before the question finishes, mistaking the first clever thing you said for what you actually think. Once a day, let a question sit for ten full seconds before you touch it. What surfaces in that gap is the opinion worth having.",
    4: "Home, for you, is wherever the wifi and the conversation are good — and you have had a lot of homes. You rearrange furniture the way other people change moods, keep books in every room including the bathroom, and go quietly feral in a household where nobody talks at dinner. Your family history is a collection of stories told differently by everyone who was there, and you are the one who noticed the versions do not match.\n\nYou come from people who talked around things, so you learned to treat lightness as safety — keep it moving, keep it funny, never let the room go still. The trap: you treat your own home like a layover, never fully unpacking, emotionally or literally. Choose one place — one room, even — and let it actually know you. Roots are not a cage; they are bandwidth.",
    5: "Nobody flirts like you. Banter is your foreplay, and the person who can return your serve — quick, dry, slightly dangerous — owns your attention completely. You fall for minds first and faces second, court people through voice notes and inside jokes, and your idea of romance is a conversation that starts at dinner and is somehow still going at 3 a.m. With kids, with art, with play, it is the same engine: you are the one inventing the game, changing the rules, keeping everyone laughing.\n\nThe honest problem is that you are addicted to opening chapters. When the wordplay settles into routine, you read it as death instead of depth, and you start scanning the room. The trap: abandoning good love at the exact moment it stops performing. When boredom hits, ask a harder question instead of finding a new person.",
    6: "You cannot do the same task the same way two days running — your body physically resists it. So you have built a working life out of juggling: three projects, headphones in, browser tabs like a city skyline, thriving on exactly the chaos that would flatten your coworkers. You are the person who fixes the process nobody realized was broken, mostly because you were too bored to follow it.\n\nYour health runs through your nerves: when your mind is overfed, you sleep badly, skip lunch, and grind your teeth through emails you never answer. The trap: mistaking motion for progress — a day of forty small tasks that adds up to nothing you can point at. Every morning, name the one thing that must ship, do it before the noise starts, and then let yourself scatter with a clear conscience.",
    7: "You married — or will marry — a conversation. The bond that holds you is the one where the talk never runs dry: the debrief after the party, the debate over nothing, the person who texts you the exact article you were about to send them. Silent companionship reads to you as malfunction; you check the connection by talking, and you know something is wrong in the relationship days before they do, because the sentences got shorter.\n\nYou keep it light on purpose — humor is how you love, and also how you dodge. The trap: turning every hard feeling into a debate you can win, so your partner ends up out-argued but unheard. When they bring you something raw, put down the counterpoint. Say \"tell me more\" and mean it. Being right is not the same as being close.",
    8: "You can talk about anything — death, debt, desire, the thing your family never mentions — with a fluency that unnerves people. You are the one asking the widow real questions at the funeral, reading about grief while grieving, googling the diagnosis at 2 a.m. and arriving at the appointment better informed than the doctor. Curiosity is how you metabolize the unbearable, and honestly, it works — up to a point.\n\nThe point is your own body. When intimacy or crisis gets close enough to touch you, you climb up into commentary: narrating the feeling instead of having it, delivering the eulogy for an emotion that is not done with you yet. The trap: everyone assumes you have processed it because you can explain it. Once, with someone safe, let a feeling finish before you give it words.",
    9: "You have sampled more belief systems than most people have read about: the meditation phase, the philosophy-podcast phase, the semester of a language you now use only to order food. Travel, for you, is eavesdropping on how other minds work — you come home from every trip with a new opinion and someone's number. You would make a brilliant teacher precisely because you refuse to stop being a student.\n\nBut ask what you actually believe and watch yourself do the thing: cite three thinkers, hold four positions, commit to none. Standing somewhere feels like closing a door, and you keep every door open on principle. The trap: a lifetime of fascinating opinions and no operating philosophy on the day real loss shows up needing one. Write down the three things you believe enough to act on — then act on them.",
    10: "Your resume confuses recruiters and impresses everyone else. You have had careers, plural — or one career that reinvents itself every few years — and your professional superpower is translation: taking what the technical people said and making the decision-makers actually understand it. You are known as the fast one, the articulate one, the person you want in the room when the message matters more than the spreadsheet.\n\nWhat you are not yet known as is the authority — because authority requires staying past the point where it stops being interesting. The trap: pivoting at year three, every time, right before the compounding starts, so you remain the promising generalist watching duller people collect the expert's paycheck. Pick the one lane you would still find questions in at year ten, and let your range become depth's supporting act.",
    11: "Your phone contains multitudes: the group chat from the old job, the group chat from the hobby, the people you met in line once and somehow kept. You are the human switchboard of every circle you touch — the one who introduces two friends and accidentally creates a marriage, a company, a band. Communities form around you without your planning it, because you ask questions at parties the way other people eat appetizers.\n\nBut count the people who have seen you cry. That number is the audit. The trap: two hundred people who would happily get coffee with you, two who would drive to you at midnight — and you keep watering the two hundred. Choose three friendships and start telling them the unfunny truth. A network reposts your wins; only friends carry your losses.",
    12: "There is no off switch in your head — only a night shift. Lying in the dark, you replay conversations, draft comebacks for arguments that ended years ago, and hold entire imaginary dialogues vivid enough that you wake up tired from them. The commentary that charms everyone all day turns on you the moment you are alone, and it knows exactly where to aim.\n\nWhat you hide from everyone is how loud it gets in there. You, the great communicator, keep a whole interior wing of thoughts you have never said out loud to anyone. The trap: the unspoken spirals ferment — a worry you will not voice becomes a truth you start obeying. Get it out of your skull daily: journal, voice memo, one honest friend. A thought written down is half its size; a thought kept whispers all night.",
  },
  Libra: {
    1: "Charm is your front door, and it opens before you decide to open it. You walk in already calibrating — reading the room's temperature, softening your voice to match it, angling yourself toward whoever looks left out. People describe you as lovely before they can tell you why. Even your appearance is diplomacy: put together, never loud, dressed as an answer to the question of what would put everyone at ease.\n\nHere is what that costs. You have spent so long being what each room needed that your own preferences arrive muffled and secondhand, as if you are being polite even to yourself. The trap: an identity assembled entirely from other people's comfort — agreeable, adored, and vague. Next time someone asks where you want to eat, answer in under five seconds with an actual place. Start there. It scales.",
    2: "You will pay extra for the beautiful version of anything — the phone case, the notebook, the apartment with worse plumbing and better light. Money moves through your hands as taste: curation, upgrades, gifts chosen with unsettling precision. And you earn it socially, too — people hire you, promote you, refer you, because being genuinely pleasant to work with turns out to be a market advantage you have been compounding since childhood.\n\nBut your sense of what you are worth still runs through other people's eyes. You undercharge because asking feels rude, split bills you should not split, and buy things that photograph well for an audience you cannot name. The trap: bankrolling your own likability. Set your price, say it without a discount in your voice, and let the silence afterward just sit there. The right people do not flinch.",
    3: "You edit every sentence before it leaves your mouth — smoothing the edge, adding the softener, appending \"but I could be wrong\" to things you are not wrong about. You rewrite the blunt text three times, translate between feuding friends, and can deliver criticism so gracefully the person thanks you for it. Words, in your hands, are furniture arrangement: everything placed so nobody bumps into anything sharp.\n\nThe cost hides in plain sight: after all that balancing, nobody — including you — knows what you actually think. Every opinion you voice comes pre-loaded with its own counterargument, and people have learned they can push, because you will accommodate. The trap: a lifetime of \"either works for me\" hardening into invisibility. Once a day, state a preference plainly. No softener, no question mark, no \"but\".",
    4: "The people you grew up with made you the referee. Somewhere in childhood you learned to read a slammed cupboard like a weather report, and you have been managing household atmospheres ever since — seating feuding relatives apart, changing subjects at dinner with surgical timing, absorbing tension so the room does not have to. Your home now is your rebuttal: soft light, flowers, everything arranged, a place engineered for the peace you rarely got to simply receive.\n\nBut notice what keeps the peace in your house: your silence. You swallow the complaint, smooth the moment, and file the grievance somewhere it does not stay filed. The trap: a beautiful home with an unspoken argument in every drawer. Raise the small issue this week, at the kitchen table, while it is still small. Real peace survives a raised voice; yours has never been tested.",
    5: "You fall in love with courtship itself — the anticipation, the outfit, the table by the window, the message crafted and sent at exactly the right hour. Dating you is cinematic, and everyone says so. Romance is your art form and also your actual art: whatever you make, you make with an audience's eye, and the polish shows. Even your play is composed; even your fun is curated.\n\nThe tell is who you choose. You have dated people who looked correct — right laugh, right jacket, right effect on your friends — and felt lonely at beautiful dinners with them. The trap: casting a partner instead of meeting one, then wondering why the scene feels empty when the camera is off. Next time, notice how you feel around someone when you look terrible. Choose whoever makes that feel fine.",
    6: "You do your best work next to someone. Solo tasks drag; give you a collaborator, a shared doc, a two-person project, and suddenly you are brilliant. At work you are the resident diplomat — the one who translates between the difficult manager and the wounded team, whose desk has somehow become the place people stop to decompress. You keep the environment pleasant because you literally cannot function in an ugly, tense one: bad lighting and passive aggression make you ill in ways you have stopped trying to explain.\n\nAnd that is the medical fact of you: your body keeps minutes for every conflict you smoothed over. The headaches, the flattening fatigue — that is absorbed friction. The trap: becoming the workplace's unpaid shock absorber and calling it your personality. Once a week, decline to mediate something. Let two adults have their conflict without you.",
    7: "Partnership is your native language — you were fluent in \"we\" before you had a \"me\" fully drafted. You think in twos: the trip becomes real when there is someone to turn to on the train, the joke lands when there is a specific person to text it to. In love you are attentive, fair, genuinely gifted — you remember the anniversary and the argument's actual point, and you negotiate like the relationship is a small country you are honored to govern.\n\nBut watch what happens when your person is upset with you: you fold before the disagreement even opens. You would rather concede than collide, apologize than clarify, stay than face the conversation that leaving requires. The trap: keeping the peace until you have traded away the entire territory of yourself. Fight one fair fight all the way through. A bond that cannot survive it was already over.",
    8: "Even in the deep end, you are keeping things fair. Merging money, merging lives, sitting in the wreckage of a crisis — you are the one proposing the equitable split, the reasonable process, the civilized divorce. You bring elegance to situations that have none, and people are grateful, because someone has to stay graceful while everything burns.\n\nBut intimacy at full depth is not fair, and that is precisely what unnerves you. Real merging is messy, needy, occasionally ugly — and you keep trying to negotiate terms with something that does not take meetings. Meanwhile you keep a ledger you would never admit to: who gave more, who apologized last, tallied silently in the dark. The trap: scorekeeping disguised as fairness — resentment with good posture. Show someone the ugly want before you have made it presentable. Depth begins where your manners end.",
    9: "Strangers assume you are a lawyer, because you argue both sides of anything that well — and friends have stopped asking your opinion, because they know they will get a beautifully balanced survey instead. Injustice is the one thing that cracks your composure: you will go to the mat for fairness in the abstract, for other people, for principle. You study through conversation, believe through dialogue, and every philosophy you have ever adopted arrived via someone you loved talking to.\n\nBut symmetry is not truth, and some questions have a right answer you are refusing to say out loud. The trap: treating \"I see both sides\" as a permanent residence — a worldview so balanced it never tells you what to do at an actual crossroads. Take the conviction you already secretly hold, say it in public unhedged, and let someone disagree with you. Survive it. That is a belief.",
    10: "Your reputation precedes you, and it is spotless — that is not an accident; that is a body of work. Professionally you are the reasonable one, the tasteful one, the one they send in when the client is furious or the room is divided. You have built your public self with real craftsmanship: how you are seen is something you tend the way other people tend investments, and it pays like one.\n\nBut a reputation for being agreeable is a ceiling wearing a compliment's clothing. The decisions that would define your career require making someone influential unhappy, and you have already sidestepped three of them — you know their names. The trap: becoming beloved and passed over, the eternal safe pair of hands. Take the public position that costs you an admirer. The career you want is on the other side of the first person you disappoint on purpose.",
    11: "Every friend group you have ever joined got measurably more harmonious within a month — you introduce the right people, defuse the group-chat spat before it metastasizes, remember whose week was hard. You are the social architecture nobody sees: the dinner exists because you organized it, the circle holds because you are the joint. Other people assume communities simply form around them. Yours form because of you.\n\nBut being everyone's favorite has a precise cost: you are honest with no one. You have watched friends make mistakes and said nothing, held opinions about the group and voiced none, because the harmony you built feels too expensive to risk. The trap: a hundred warm connections resting on your permanent self-censorship. Tell one friend the true thing you have been withholding — kindly, but completely. Watch the friendship deepen instead of break.",
    12: "Alone is the one room you never decorated. When the plans cancel and the apartment goes quiet, something in you reads it as failure — as evidence — and you reach for your phone before the feeling can finish its sentence. All that graciousness you perform in public has a shadow ledger, kept privately: every swallowed retort, every unfair split, every time you smiled through it. You do not call it resentment. It is.\n\nThe hidden truth is that your niceness has a basement, and things live down there — envy, anger, the wish to be caught for once instead of always doing the catching. Denied, they leak: the migraine, the sudden coldness you cannot explain, the sabotage dressed as accident. The trap: rotting politely. Sit alone once a week, no phone, and write down what you are actually angry about. Read it back. Believe it.",
  },
  Aquarius: {
    1: "You arrive at the party as its anthropologist. While everyone else performs belonging, you are at the edge with a drink, watching the mating rituals with detached fondness — and somehow this makes people cross the room toward you. Your first impression is a paradox: friendly and unreachable at once, dressed slightly wrong on purpose, opening with the observation nobody else would say. People remember meeting you. They cannot remember feeling like they got close.\n\nThe distance is real, and it started early — somewhere back there you decided that being fully seen was a security risk, and \"the interesting outsider\" became your bodyguard. The trap: performing strangeness so consistently that it becomes its own conformity, a costume you cannot take off even for people you love. Every so often, walk into a room and just be ordinary in it. Nobody dies.",
    2: "For months at a time, money sits beneath your attention — possessions are clutter, wealth is a rigged scoreboard, and you would rather fund the idea than buy the couch. Then one invoice lands wrong and you are doing spreadsheet archaeology at 2 a.m. Your income has never been normal anyway: the unusual niche, the freelance orbit, the job title your parents cannot explain to their friends. You own six of some strange thing and zero of something basic.\n\nHere is the wiring underneath: you treat needing money as a design flaw you are above, which means you never build the boring systems that would make you actually free. The trap: principled indifference collapsing into crisis management, on a loop. Automate the unglamorous minimum — a buffer, a transfer, one number checked weekly — so your ideals stop being hostage to your cash flow.",
    3: "You think sideways. In any conversation you are two exits ahead, connecting the thing just said to a system nobody else noticed it belonged to, and your mouth ships the conclusion without the comforting preamble. People call you blunt; you call it efficient. You are the sibling who blew up the family consensus at dinner, the friend who answers \"how are you\" with a theory, the texter who sends a link at midnight with no context and expects delight.\n\nYour ideas are genuinely original — that was never the issue. The issue is that you would rather be correct than connected, and small talk feels like being asked to run in place. The trap: winning the point and losing the person, over and over, then wondering why insight has not bought you intimacy. Before your next correction, ask one question about how they got there.",
    4: "You were the odd one at your own family table — the kid whose questions made the adults exchange looks, who figured out early that home was a system and systems can be wrong. So you built your real family later, by hand: the friends who became fixtures, the door that is always open, the house that runs less like a nest and more like a headquarters. Your holiday table has strays at it, and that is the thing you are proudest of.\n\nBut the distance from your roots is not as clean as you tell it. \"I was always different\" is a story that protects you from a plainer one: it hurt, and it still routes your decisions. The trap: keeping every home at arm's length because the first one did not fit — exile as a lifestyle. Ask one member of your first family a real question about their life. You have studied strangers more carefully.",
    5: "You have never once had a normal crush. The people who catch you are the anomalies — the odd laugh, the strange job, the mind that refuses to sit in its assigned category — and your courtship style is essentially research: fascinated questions, sudden 3 a.m. theories about them, affection delivered as banter from a slightly ironic distance. Your creativity works the same way; you do not decorate ideas, you invent formats. Play, for you, means breaking the game to see what it does.\n\nBut watch yourself the moment fascination turns into feeling: you convert the emotion into commentary, studying your own falling-in-love like a lab result instead of letting it wreck you a little. The trap: dating like a researcher and calling the resulting distance independence. Tell someone what you feel while you still feel it — unedited, untheorized, in the moment it is happening.",
    6: "A rule that cannot defend itself does not survive contact with you. Every job you have had, you found the pointless procedure in week one and either fixed it, automated it, or quietly stopped doing it to see if anyone noticed. Your daily systems are ingenious and completely nonstandard — the workflow nobody taught you, the schedule that ignores the clock, the health regimen built on your own data because generic advice offends you. Given permission to redesign the machine, you are the best employee in the building.\n\nThe glitch: your rebellion does not distinguish between other people's arbitrary rules and your own good ones. The routine you designed last month is now the authority you are resisting. The trap: reinventing your habits so often that nothing compounds — perpetual system, no results. Keep one boring practice unchanged for ninety days. Freedom includes the freedom to repeat yourself.",
    7: "You need a marriage that behaves like a friendship — the debrief, the running jokes, the shared project, two people facing the world together rather than staring at each other. Clinginess repels you faster than cruelty; the quickest way to lose you is to need you on a schedule. The partner who lasts is the one with a full life of their own, who finds your strangeness a feature and not a phase.\n\nBut here is your pattern under pressure: when your person gets emotional — really emotional, inconveniently emotional — you go cool and reasonable, offering analysis where they needed arms. You call it staying calm. They experience it as you leaving the room without moving. The trap: being an excellent companion and an absent partner in the same body. Next time they crack open, come physically closer instead of getting verbally smarter.",
    8: "In every crisis, you are the one who goes calm — eerily calm, making arrangements, seeing the system while everyone else drowns in the feeling. When it comes to merging money or lives, you want it rational: the shared spreadsheet, the transparent terms, arrangements your in-laws find weird and you find obviously correct. You will discuss taboos at brunch without blinking. Depth does not scare your mind at all.\n\nIt scares your body. In real intimacy — the kind with no exit and no irony — you float up out of yourself and observe, narrating the merger from the ceiling. Partners have asked you some version of \"where do you go?\" and you deflected with something clever. The trap: surviving every deep moment by not fully attending it, then calling the numbness peace. When it gets intense, say the physical feeling out loud instead of the analysis. Stay in the room you are in.",
    9: "Your beliefs are handmade. You have dismantled every doctrine you were raised with, stress-tested every popular philosophy at the dinner table, and assembled a worldview from parts — a little physics, a little mysticism you would deny in public, conclusions from strange corners of the internet and stranger corners of your travels. Study, for you, is a form of dissent: you learn things mostly to find out where the textbook is wrong.\n\nAnd it usually is — that is the seduction. But somewhere along the way, disagreeing became load-bearing. If the consensus says sky, some reflex in you starts drafting the case for ceiling. The trap: contrarianism wearing the costume of independent thought — your positions still determined by the crowd, just inverted. Find one mainstream, boring, true thing and defend it in public. Believing something popular will not dissolve you.",
    10: "No map exists for your career, because you left the mapped territory in your twenties. Your title has required explanation at every family gathering since — the hybrid role, the invented niche, the company that did not exist ten years ago or exists because of you. Professionally you are the one who says the unsayable thing in the strategy meeting, and half your reputation is other people quoting it later, without credit, as common sense.\n\nBut track your pattern near the summit: every time conventional success gets close — the title, the institution, the establishment's embrace — you find a reason to swerve. Some part of you believes that being accepted means being assimilated. The trap: sabotaging your own arrival to protect your outsider license. Take the seat at the table when it is offered. You can change more from inside the room than critiquing it through the window.",
    11: "Your people are plural and scattered: the online collective, the old crew, the strangers who became a movement, group chats spanning four time zones with no common thread except you. You think in futures — what the community becomes, what the world does next decade — and your friends treat you as the one who saw it coming. Causes find you; you cannot watch a broken system without organizing something.\n\nBut here is the audit that stings: you love humanity fluently and individual humans intermittently. The friend whose crisis is boring, ongoing, and unfixable gets your theory of their problem instead of your Tuesday. The trap: caring at scale as a way to avoid caring at close range, where it actually costs you something. Pick one person and show up repeatedly, in person, for something that does not interest you. That is the future too.",
    12: "The detachment everyone assumes is your temperament is actually your architecture — built, not born. Alone at night, off the record, you are far more haunted than anyone who knows you would guess: strange dreams that feel like transmissions, a grief about the state of the world you carry like a second job, and underneath the observer's cool, a longing to belong so old you have classified it as unsolvable. You, the friend of everyone, feel like a guest species.\n\nHere is the machinery: you decided long ago that needing people was the one system failure you could not afford, so you optimized it away — and named the result independence. The trap: your detachment is a fire exit you now live in. Tell one trusted person, \"I get lonelier than I look.\" That sentence will cost you the persona and buy you the belonging.",
  },
};

const FUSION_WATER: Record<string, Record<number, string>> = {
  Cancer: {
    1: "You read a room before you enter it — pausing at the threshold, scanning for who is safe, who is hurting, where the exits are. People sense it: strangers hand you their sadness within minutes of meeting you, because your face does something that says it will be held. Your body keeps score in real time — your stomach knots before your mind admits anything is wrong, and everyone can watch the weather move across your face whether you like it or not.\n\nYou lead with warmth, then retreat the instant it isn't returned — one cool glance and you pull back into politeness so smooth nobody can prove you left. The trap: people experience your self-protection as rejection and quietly stop reaching for you. Stay in the room thirty seconds past the flinch, and say what stung.",
    2: "Money is not math to you — it is shelter. A full pantry, a padded savings account, a drawer of objects you refuse to throw out because they remember something: this is how you convince your nervous system the storm can come. You don't buy status; you buy safety, and you can recite from memory the lean seasons that taught you to. You still own gifts from people who are long gone.\n\nBecause your bank balance and your sense of being okay are wired together, a dip in one crashes the other, and you'll cancel joy in a flush month because a lean one is theoretically coming. The trap: no number ever feels like enough, so you keep moving the goalpost and calling it prudence. Write down the actual figure that means safe — then let yourself spend past it.",
    3: "You remember tone. Not just what your sister said in 2019 — the exact pitch of it, the pause before it, what the kitchen smelled like. Conversation is never information exchange for you; every sentence arrives with an emotional temperature you clock instantly, which is why an offhand comment can ruin your afternoon while a kind word from the right person carries you for a week. You check in on people constantly. Your texts are casseroles.\n\nThe problem is you expect everyone to hear the way you hear, so when you're hurt you go quiet and wait to be decoded — dropping hints, cooling your replies, certain the silence speaks. It doesn't. The trap: punishing people for missing messages you never actually sent. Say the plain sentence — I felt dismissed when you said that — and watch how much faster it heals.",
    4: "Home is not the backdrop of your life; it is the plot. You are the one who keeps the recipes, the photographs, the birthdays, the story of the family — the unofficial archivist everyone relies on and nobody thanks. Your door is the softest place your people know, and you like it that way: feeding someone at your own table is the closest thing you have to prayer.\n\nBut the harbor that shelters you also holds you. You replay childhood rooms, re-litigate old kitchen arguments, and measure every current home against one that exists only in memory. The trap: staying loyal to a family story that costs you your adult life — living where you're needed instead of where you'd grow. Keep the recipes, keep the people, and let one tradition end with you on purpose.",
    5: "You don't flirt so much as adopt. The moment someone charms you, you start feeding them — literally, emotionally, logistically — and your idea of a love affair looks suspiciously like building a nest around a person who hasn't agreed to live in one yet. Your creativity works the same way: everything you make is a diary in disguise, which is why criticism of your work lands like criticism of your childhood. Around children you become the safest adult in the building, and they know it on sight.\n\nTenderness is your love language and your leverage — when it isn't returned in kind, you sulk instead of saying so, withdrawing the warmth to see if they notice. The trap: smothering what you love until it wriggles free just to breathe. Give the gift once, then wait — let them cross the room to you.",
    6: "Within a month at any new job you know who skips lunch, whose marriage is shaking, and which coworker needs checking on — and you've quietly appointed yourself responsible for all of it. You feed offices. You absorb workplace moods the way a sponge absorbs spills, and your body files every swallowed frustration in your gut: the tight stomach on Sunday night is not a mystery, it's an inventory.\n\nBecause you serve by instinct, you overfunction by default — covering shifts, soothing tempers, performing invisible labor that appears on no job description and no paycheck. The trap: caretaking your way into resentment and then into actual illness, since your digestion goes on strike long before you ever will. Drop one task you were never asked to carry, this week, and watch nothing collapse.",
    7: "You fall in love with people's needs. A partner's bad day activates you like a fire alarm — you're cooking, soothing, solving before they've finished the sentence, and you read their moods so fluently you often know they're upset before they do. Being needed is how you feel secure in a bond; a self-sufficient partner unsettles you more than a demanding one ever could.\n\nHere is the ledger you pretend not to keep: every soup, every sacrifice, every mood you managed — recorded, unpaid. Eventually you present the bill in the currency of hurt silence, and your partner is bewildered because they never knew they were borrowing. The trap: turning yourself into their parent, then resenting that the marriage stopped feeling like romance. Once a week, ask to be taken care of — out loud, specifically — and let them do it badly.",
    8: "When someone lets you in, you build them a room inside yourself — and you never fully evict anyone. Exes, dead relatives, the friend who vanished a decade ago: they all still live in there, visited regularly. You merge completely or not at all; sharing a bank account, a bed, a crisis with you means being held with a grip that does not loosen just because things end. In actual disaster you are shockingly capable — the one who sits with the dying, handles the estate, holds the family together.\n\nBut your loyalty outlives its objects. You keep paying emotional rent on condemned buildings, staying attached to what already left. The trap: calling it devotion when it is a refusal to grieve. Pick one thing you have already lost and mourn it properly — with an ending, on purpose — instead of keeping it on life support.",
    9: "Your beliefs smell like your grandmother's kitchen. Whatever faith or philosophy you hold, you didn't reason your way there — it was handed to you warm, at a table, by people you loved, and defending it feels like defending them. You travel the same way: even in a foreign city you find a favorite café, a familiar walk, a waiter who knows your order within days — building a small home wherever you land, then aching for the one you left.\n\nYou learn best through story and memory, not argument, which makes you a wonderful teacher and a stubborn student. The trap: mistaking familiar for true — keeping a worldview because leaving it feels like betraying your family, not because it still holds. Once a year, read something that would scandalize the dinner table, all the way through.",
    10: "Colleagues bring you their crises before they bring them to HR. Whatever your title says, your actual role is identical everywhere you've worked: the one who notices, who remembers, who makes the team feel like a family — and your reputation is built on being trustworthy in exactly that way. Criticism of your work hits you like criticism of your character, because you never learned to separate what you do from who you are.\n\nMeanwhile your ambition hides inside your helpfulness. You want the corner office and pretend you only want everyone fed, so you wait to be promoted for devotion instead of asking for what you've earned. The trap: mothering an organization for a decade and calling the resentment loyalty. Say the actual number, the actual title, in the actual meeting — nurturers are allowed to want things.",
    11: "Your friendships have anniversaries. The group chat you run is fifteen years old, you remember every birthday without an app, and when a friend gives birth or buries a parent, you're on the doorstep with food before anyone else has finished typing thoughts and prayers. You don't collect friends; you keep them — a small, fiercely tended circle that functions as your chosen family.\n\nThe tending has a wall around it, though. Newcomers get years of polite distance before admission, and you quietly grieve every change in the group — the friend who moved, the dynamic that shifted — as if change were betrayal. The trap: guarding the circle so tightly it slowly becomes a museum of who you all used to be. At the next gathering, invite one new person, and let the chemistry rearrange.",
    12: "There is a version of you no one has met — softer, sadder, more tired than the capable person you present — and it only comes out when the door is locked. You need withdrawal the way other people need exercise: hours of solitude where you finally feel everything you postponed all week. You cry alone, almost on a schedule, and emerge reassembled. You also carry sorrow that predates you — a heaviness from your family line that was never named at any table you sat at, so it settled in you.\n\nThe retreating is healthy; the secrecy around it isn't. You vanish mid-crisis without telling anyone, and the people who love you learn your closed door instead of your reasons. The trap: hiding and calling it self-care. Disappear all you need — just leave a note saying when you're coming back.",
  },
  Scorpio: {
    1: "Rooms adjust to you. You walk in quietly, give away nothing, and somehow everyone recalibrates — people either lean toward you or check the exits, and both reactions are correct. You watch faces the way accountants watch ledgers, cataloguing tells, and strangers routinely say they felt seen through within a minute of meeting you. Your resting expression is a locked door with excellent lighting.\n\nThe control is the point: you decided long ago that whoever shows their hand first loses, so your face releases only what you've cleared for publication. But a permanently guarded person can be admired, feared, studied — never actually reached. The trap: winning every first impression and losing every chance at being known. Once a day, let a reaction escape unedited — a laugh too loud, a hurt uncovered — and notice that nobody uses it against you.",
    2: "Nobody knows what you make. Not your friends, not your family, sometimes not even your partner — your finances are classified, and you enjoy the asymmetry of knowing everyone else's situation while yours stays sealed. Money is never just money to you; it is leverage, exit routes, proof that no one can ever again hold power over you the way someone once did. You go all-in or scorched-earth: extreme saving, extreme risk, nothing in between.\n\nBecause resources equal control in your gut, sharing them feels like handing over a weapon — so you keep quiet cushions and escape funds inside relationships you'd call committed. The trap: the hidden money becomes a hidden loyalty, and the person beside you can feel the vault they can't see. Open the books to one person completely. Solvency you already have; being trusted with is the richer thing.",
    3: "You have never made small talk in your life. Within three questions you're asking about someone's divorce, their fear, the thing they came to the party to avoid — and people answer you, which still surprises them. You listen like a detective: the pause before the answer tells you more than the answer, and you file everything. Verbatim. For years. Your family learned long ago that you cannot be lied to, only avoided.\n\nYour memory for words is a gift right up until you're angry, when it becomes an arsenal — you can quote a confession from 2017 with the timestamp, and you aim it where it will do structural damage. The trap: winning arguments with ammunition people handed you in trust, which teaches everyone to stop handing you anything. Keep the vault sealed during combat. Fight with today's grievance only.",
    4: "You are most yourself in the one place almost nobody is allowed to see. Out in the world you perform competence, control, even charm — but your actual life happens behind your own front door, and you guard that door like it's load-bearing. It is. Home isn't where you relax; it's where you regenerate, and anyone allowed in there has passed tests you never told them they were taking.\n\nYou inherited more than furniture from your family — you carry their unfinished emotional business, the things that were felt but never said in the house you grew up in. Part of your life's work is deciding which of those inheritances end with you. The trap: you'll burn a relationship to the ground in private and never tell the person there was a fire. Say the thing while it's still small — the people who belong in your inner room can handle it.",
    5: "You do not have crushes; you have investigations. When someone catches your interest you learn everything — their history, their patterns, their exes — before the second date, and what you call romance most people would call total immersion. Play needs stakes for you: you'd rather lose big at something real than win politely at something safe. Whatever you create comes up from the basement — art, projects, even jokes with an edge that makes people laugh and flinch at once. Children get your fiercest, most undivided devotion; you love them like a bodyguard.\n\nBut you test what you desire. You set little trials — withdrawing to see who pursues, provoking to see who stays — and call the results data. The trap: engineering the exact abandonment you were screening for. Once, love something without auditing it: no tests, no files, just the afternoon.",
    6: "Your routines are not habits; they are security systems. The same wake time, the same workout, the schedule defended like a border — you control your days because your days are the one thing you can control. At work you go subterranean: obsessive focus, zero delegation, and a private conviction that you're the only one who does it right. Your body keeps a ledger of everything you refuse to feel, and it collects — the clenched jaw, the gut, the insomnia that arrives precisely when you've been strongest the longest.\n\nYour rhythm is binary: monk-like discipline for months, then a spectacular demolition of every rule in one weekend, then shame, then stricter rules. The trap: building regimes so severe that rebellion is the only rest available. Schedule the slack on purpose — a lazy day inside the system, so it never has to become an uprising.",
    7: "Marriage, to you, is a merger with no exit clause — you would rather stay alone for a decade than commit at sixty percent. When you finally choose someone, you choose all the way: their debts, their nightmares, their history become yours, and you defend the bond with a loyalty most people reserve for blood. You know your partner's secrets, including the ones they never told you.\n\nThat last part is the tell. You gather intelligence inside your own relationship — the phone left face-down, the changed password, the pause before an answer — because trusting blind feels like exposing your throat. So you verify instead of asking, and every act of surveillance quietly announces that you expect betrayal. Expected things have a way of arriving. The trap: interrogating a loyal person until leaving looks like their only innocence. Ask the direct question first — you can handle any answer.",
    8: "Other people's emergencies are your natural habitat. When the diagnosis lands, the marriage detonates, the estate needs settling, everyone else goes pale and you go calm — you have never once flinched at the unspeakable, which is why people bring you what they can't say in daylight. You hold more confessions than most priests: the affairs, the addictions, the real reasons. Shared money, shared beds, shared catastrophe — you operate at depths that would drown the people around you.\n\nNotice the traffic pattern, though: secrets flow toward you and nothing flows back. You are everyone's vault and no one's confider, intimate with the whole world's underside while your own stays sealed. The trap: mistaking being trusted for being close — a one-way confessional is not a relationship. Hand your heaviest secret to one person who has earned it, and let them hold you for once.",
    9: "Every belief you hold has survived an execution attempt. You don't adopt philosophies; you interrogate them — stress-testing teachers, hunting the fraud inside every stated ideal — and whatever is still standing afterward earns your rare, ferocious conviction. You read what others won't: death, power, the forbidden shelf, the histories everyone agreed to forget. Your travel itineraries skip the beaches for the catacombs.\n\nSomewhere along the way, demolition became your religion. You've torn down so many faiths — inherited ones, adopted ones, other people's — that disbelief itself hardened into a creed, and you defend your cynicism with the exact fervor you distrust in believers. The trap: calling it clarity when it is armor against ever being fooled again. Keep one conviction you cannot prove — let a single sacred thing stay uninterrogated, and see what grows there.",
    10: "You play the long game while everyone else plays the quarter. Your career runs on strategy nobody sees coming: within weeks of joining any organization you've mapped who actually holds power, you say little in meetings, and you move only after everyone else has shown their cards. Your reputation is deliberately incomplete — colleagues who've known you for years cannot summarize you, which is exactly the design. People who crossed you professionally still tell the story, carefully.\n\nBut the vigilance that carried you up becomes a bunker at altitude. You read rivals into loyal colleagues, hold grudges past their usefulness, and treat transparency like a wardrobe malfunction. The trap: winning the position and salting the ground around it, so the top is exactly as lonely as you secretly predicted. Spend some power generously — champion someone publicly, with nothing to gain — and watch it return doubled.",
    11: "Your friendships come with a vetting period measured in years. Crowds bore you and group loyalty strikes you as naive, so your circle is four people, five at most, each of whom passed trials they never knew were running — and for those few you would drive at 3 a.m., testify in court, bury whatever needs burying. Acquaintances call you aloof; your real friends know you're the most devoted person they've ever met.\n\nYour exits are famous. When someone fails a test, they're gone — unfollowed, unanswered, erased — and they never learn which line they crossed, because trials you don't announce can't be appealed. The trap: a shrinking circle that reads as discernment and functions as isolation. Before the next door slams, say the sentence: here is what you did. Give one person the chance to repair it.",
    12: "The most dangerous secrets you keep are the ones you keep from yourself. You've buried things so deep — an old shame, a grief you never processed, a rage you decided was unacceptable — that you genuinely forgot the burial sites, and now they run the show from underground: the sabotage before every breakthrough, the sudden exits from good things, the 3 a.m. dread with no return address. Your dreams do the excavation your waking mind refuses — vivid, recurring, and right.\n\nYou transform constantly, but always in private: nobody watches you molt, and by design nobody could help. The trap: treating your own depths as a solo assignment, punishing yourself in secret for crimes no one charged you with. Say the buried thing out loud to one person — a friend, a therapist, anyone. Spoken, it's a story. Buried, it's a landmine.",
  },
  Pisces: {
    1: "Strangers tell you their life stories in checkout lines. Something in your face reads as no judgment here, and people respond to it before you've said a word — you have been a confessor on airplanes, a therapist at bus stops, a shoulder at parties where you knew no one. You arrive in rooms like weather rather than a person: soft-edged, atmospheric, taking on the emotional temperature of whoever stands closest. By evening you often can't tell which feelings you brought and which you caught.\n\nBecause you mirror so instinctively, you become whoever each room requires — funnier here, quieter there — and everyone likes the version they get. The trap: shapeshifting so fluently that no one, including you, knows what you're actually like. When you walk in, state one plain preference — where to sit, what to drink — and hold it.",
    2: "You could not say what's in your checking account right now, and that vagueness is a choice disguised as a personality. Money moves through you like water through cupped hands — you lend without recording, tip like an apology, give to whoever asks, and treat looking at your balance as a violence best avoided. Possessions barely register: you lose umbrellas, give away books, and feel more secure after donating than after saving.\n\nUnderneath the generosity is an equation you never examine: being needed feels like worth, so you fund other people's lives while your own runs on fumes and faith. The trap: rescuing everyone's finances except yours, then calling the eventual crash bad luck. Open the account every Sunday, eyes open, ten minutes. The numbers are kinder than the dread — and they only rescue people who look at them.",
    3: "You answer questions people haven't asked yet. Mid-conversation you respond to what someone meant rather than what they said, and you're right often enough to be unsettling. Your thoughts move in images and tides, not bullet points — you forget the address but remember the light in the room, lose the argument but absorb the ache underneath it. Your sentences trail off because you assume the other person is already there with you.\n\nOften they aren't. Your drift leaves gaps, and people fill them with their own assumptions, then act on words you never said — so you feel chronically misquoted by your own conversations. The trap: letting vagueness pass for connection until a misunderstanding you could have prevented detonates. Finish the sentence. Land the point. Say the actual words — I need this by Friday — and let the poetry rest sometimes.",
    4: "Your childhood comes back to you in weather — a certain rain, a certain song, and you're eight years old again, though what you remember and what happened have quietly parted ways. You keep a soft-focus filter over your family history, editing the painful scenes into something more bearable, and your relatives learned early that you would absorb whatever the household couldn't process: the tension, the sadness, the things nobody said. You still do it at every family dinner, driving home with a heaviness that isn't yours.\n\nHome, now, has to be a sanctuary — candles, water sounds, a door that closes — because it's where you drain what you soaked up everywhere else. The trap: nostalgia so generous it keeps you loyal to people who hurt you. Name one true memory without the filter. You can love your family and stop editing for them.",
    5: "You fall in love with who someone could be — you meet the rough draft and see the finished novel, and you're gone. Your romances start at full immersion: the soundtrack, the destiny narrative, the certainty that this one is different, all before the third date. When you make things — and you must make things, it moves through you like a current — your best work arrives as if dictated rather than built. Children adore you because you never fully renounced their citizenship; you play for real.\n\nThe heartbreak pattern is identical every time: the person eventually behaves like themselves instead of your projection, and you grieve someone who never existed. The trap: falling for your own imagination and billing the other person when it fades. For one month, date only what's in front of you — no soundtrack, no novel. See who's actually there.",
    6: "You cannot do meaningless work — a paycheck without a purpose makes you ill, sometimes literally, since your body speaks in vague symptoms whenever your spirit objects: the fatigue no test explains, the headaches that vanish on vacation. At work you're the unofficial chaplain, absorbing every colleague's troubles until you've done a full shift of emotional labor before lunch. Your routines dissolve on contact — the morning schedule, the meal plan, all of it lasts eleven days, then mist.\n\nService is your gift and your leak: you give past empty because stopping feels like abandoning someone, then crash and call the crash mysterious. The trap: martyring yourself inside a job or a schedule so porous that your health becomes the boundary you refused to set. Fix one anchor and defend it — the same bedtime, every night, no exceptions. Structure isn't your cage; it's your container.",
    7: "Within months of any serious relationship, you've adopted their taste in music, their opinions, their sleep schedule — you dissolve into partnership like sugar into water, and the sweetness is real but so is the disappearance. You're drawn to people who need saving: the brilliant but wounded, the almost-ready, the ones whose potential you can see and they can't. Loving them feels like a calling. You forgive on a loop, extending grace long past the point anyone else would have walked.\n\nBut rescuing is not relating, and a bond built on their wounds needs the wounds to survive — part of you keeps choosing patients so you never have to be seen as one. The trap: calling it unconditional love when it's actually a job you can't quit. Next crisis, don't dive in. Stand on the shore, stay warm, and let them swim it.",
    8: "When you merge with someone, you leave no lifeboat. Intimacy for you is total — body, bank account, nightmares, all poured in without a receipt — and you feel your lover's pain with such accuracy that you register their bad day before they text. Joint finances go the same way: you sign what they hand you, trust past the evidence, and treat asking questions about shared money as unromantic. Crisis reveals you: while others panic, you go strangely peaceful, at home in the deep end.\n\nThe drowning risk is real, though. You dissolve so completely into another person that when it ends — and you never plan for that — you can't locate what was yours. The trap: mistaking self-erasure for devotion. Keep one thing sovereign — an account, a room, a friendship they don't share — not as an exit, but as a self.",
    9: "You have never met a philosophy you couldn't feel your way into. The cathedral moves you, the physics lecture moves you, the tarot deck moves you — you're built for belief the way some people are built for doubt, and your bookshelf is a comparative religion syllabus assembled by longing. Travel, for you, is pilgrimage even when you call it vacation: you go places to dissolve, to be a stranger, to feel the size of things.\n\nYour openness is real wisdom right up until it becomes an open door with no screen. You swallow teachers whole — the guru, the podcast prophet, the charismatic friend — donating your discernment along with your attention. The trap: confusing being moved with being shown the truth, then following whoever moved you most recently. Test every teacher by how they treat the unimportant people in the room. Feel everything; follow almost nothing.",
    10: "Your resume reads like a novel with a wandering plot — careers you drifted into, jobs that found you, callings you followed until the tide changed. You cannot climb ladders; you can only answer summons, and the work that finally fits will have healing, beauty, or meaning at its center, because you'd rather earn less at something that matters than more at something that doesn't. Publicly you're seen as gifted and slightly unknowable — people sense there's more to you than you show.\n\nThere is, and that's the problem: you hide your ambition even from yourself, waiting to be discovered like a message in a bottle while less talented people announce themselves ashore. The trap: calling your avoidance humility and letting the dream stay safely hypothetical. Say the actual goal out loud, to another human, with a date attached. Discovery is not coming; declaration works.",
    11: "Every stray finds you. Your circle of friends is a gorgeous, improbable collage — the recovering addict, the heiress, the poet, the electrician — because you've never once sorted people by category, only by soul. You belong a little to every group and entirely to none, drifting between scenes as the beloved guest who is somehow never quite a member. What binds your people to you is your vision: you genuinely believe in a kinder future and describe it like a place you've visited.\n\nBut you're a sponge at every gathering, absorbing the room's undercurrents until you're carrying twelve people's unspoken sadness home in a borrowed coat. Then you vanish for three weeks and call it flakiness. The trap: loving everyone and reliably showing up for no one. Leave the party when you're full — but say goodbye, and name the date you'll resurface.",
    12: "Solitude isn't a preference for you; it's dialysis. After enough days among people you become staticky, blurred, full of feelings with no owners — and only hours of genuine alone time filter you back into yourself. Your inner world is enormous: dreams that continue across nights, intuitions that arrive fully formed, a private sea you've never described to anyone because language keeps failing at the shoreline.\n\nThe danger is that you have two kinds of disappearing, and you blur them on purpose. There's the retreat that restores you, and there's the escape that erodes you — the scrolling, the wine, the sleep that isn't rest, the fog pulled over whatever you don't want to face. The trap: calling the numbing a retreat until your absence becomes your life. Choose the door deliberately: real solitude, with a set return time — and tell someone which door you took.",
  },
};

